 was supposed to make sure creators knew when a video wasn’t ad-friendly, and offer them an appeals process that could get it reinstated. \u0026quot;The idea was to make this information accessible more easily, which is why some YouTubers felt that they ‘suddenly’ got a bunch of flagged videos at once,\u0026quot; wrote \u003cem\u003eKotaku’s\u003c/em\u003e Patricia Hernandez."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"5YtYQO","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"A forum post from this afternoon is even more explicit. \u0026quot;We did not change our policy of demonetizing videos that may not be appropriate for Google’s brand advertisers,\u0026quot; \u003ca href=\"https://productforums.google.com/forum/#!topic/youtube/djWE1FRqQKo\"\u003eit reads\u003c/a\u003e. \u0026quot;Nor have we changed how these policies are enforced.\u0026quot; A YouTube spokesperson told \u003cem\u003eThe Verge \u003c/em\u003ethat the flags would previously have been listed in the analytics, but a new, prominent icon in the video manager would have made it easier to see. While the email notifications would have been sent for relatively recent videos, others had probably already been demonetized for some time. Ironically, the emails were meant to make it easier to get ads reinstated, not signal a crackdown."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyPullquote","placement":{"id":"x9nRCb","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyPullquote","quote":{"html":"\u0026quot;We understand that high-quality content isn\u0026#39;t always sanitized.\u0026quot;"}},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"PnvySX","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"As \u003cem\u003eKotaku\u003c/em\u003e also notes, the rules leave a lot of leeway for advertising on supposedly inappropriate content. A video can still be ad